Crypto Weekly Intelligence Brief

Understanding the U.S. Debt vs.Deficit: By definition, a deficit is the difference between federal spending and revenue in a single fiscal year. For example, in 2024, the U.S. spent $6.5 trillion but earned only $4.9 trillion resulting in a $1.6 trillion deficit. On the other hand, the national debt is the total amount of money the government owes the accumulation of all past deficits, minus any surpluses. As of today, the U.S. national debt is approximately $35 trillion and rising exponentially.

Macro Insight: The Big Beautiful Bill and the Debt Spiral

With Congress passing what some call the big beautiful bill, the U.S. locks in $7 trillion in annual spending against just $5 trillion in revenue, locking in a $2 trillion annual deficit. Ray Dalio warns this will push national debt from 100% of GDP to 130% in a decade, with debt per household rising from ~$230K to ~$425K. Debt service alone is projected to grow from $1 trillion to $2 trillion in interest annually. This leaves policymakers with three painful options:

  • cut spending,

  • raise taxes, or more likely

  • print money and debase the currency.

Veteran analyst https://x.com/TomasOnMarkets emphasizes that the issue isnt just the size of the debt, but how its financed. Expect over $1 trillion in new issuance, likely via short-term Treasuries (yield curve control-style), which may temporarily boost risk assets but increases long-term pressure on the dollar.

Dalio reminds us: when gold or BTC go up, it might be that the dollar is going down. This is why hard money assets like gold and crypto become increasingly attractive in this environment. As debt expands and credibility erodes, the era of fiat supremacy faces a real test.

Crypto Market Conditions

Bitcoin continues to consolidate this week, holding its ground in a chaotic macro environment marked by rising government debt, geopolitical unrest, and ongoing debasement of the U.S. dollar. Altcoins are starting to heat up, showing signs of strength beneath the surface, but BTC dominance continues to suppress capital rotation. The spotlight remains firmly on Bitcoin and for good reason. Institutional and sovereign adoption is accelerating. As of July 4, over 3.4 million BTC (~16.2% of total supply) are held by institutional entities. ETFs now hold 1.43M BTC, countries 530k BTC, and public companies 857k BTC, according to Bitcoin Treasuries by Bitbo. This underscores how smart capital is migrating into hard assets amid increasing fiat fragility.

Source: https://bitbo.io/treasuries/

On-chain liquidity conditions remain healthy. The Stablecoin Supply Ratio Oscillator (SSR) from CheckOnChain continues to hover around the mid-Bollinger zone, suggesting a neutral-to-bullish liquidity environment. This means theres enough stablecoin buying power on the sidelines to fuel further upside but for now, no clear catalyst has emerged to trigger that next leg up. Historically, SSR mid-range values have preceded strong rallies once a breakout structure confirms, reinforcing the idea that conditions are primed, but not yet ignited.

Source: https://charts.checkonchain.com/btconchain/stablecoins/stablecoins_ssr_oscillator/stablecoins_ssr_oscillator_dark.html

Finally, our proprietary Dynamic Return Asymmetry Signal (DRAS) shows the market is coiled, not flat. BTC continues to act as the directional anchor, while select altcoins like SUI and SOL display strong return asymmetry suggesting they could lead the charge in the next risk-on rotation. On the flip side, coins like CRV and VET are flashing large downside anomalies, hinting at potential failed breakouts or liquidity traps. The structure is intact, capital is present, and the signal is clear: if BTC breaks out, expect a swift and aggressive altcoin rotation especially in those already showing signs of under-the-hood resilience.

Market Thesis July 7, 2025 Edition

With the U.S. locking in multi-trillion-dollar deficits and debt-to-GDP projected to hit 130% within a decade, the macro narrative is crystal clear: the fiat system is deteriorating, and capital is migrating toward hard money assets. Bitcoin sits at the center of this rotation, with institutional holdings now exceeding 3.4 million BTC (16.2% of supply), as shown in Bitbos Bitcoin Treasuries chart. This comes as global liquidity remains healthy evidenced by the Stablecoin Supply Ratio Oscillator (SSR), confirming theres ample dry powder for upside moves.

In the crypto market, BTC continues to dominate both structurally and psychologically, while select altcoins are beginning to stir. The DRAS heatmap reveals that while BTC maintains its leadership, SUI and SOL show strong asymmetric return profiles. This aligns with the SigmaSync layer signals, where BTC, ETH, and SOL flash green, indicating growing strength and likely leadership in the next leg up. Conversely, CRV and VET continue to flash red, stuck in persistent underperformance zones. Until BTC breaks out, altcoins remain in limbo but the rotation engine is warming up beneath the surface.

Conclusion A Glimpse Into the Future?

At this rate, with BTC adoption accelerating and fiat credibility declining, its not far-fetched to imagine a future where the U.S. Treasury issues bonds denominated in satoshis and central banks quote GDP in blocks mined per month. The accompanying Bitbo chart hilariously captures this trajectory: the number of satoshis required to buy 1 USD has been in freefall since 2013, and its only getting worse. Soon enough, instead of saying Bitcoin is up 2%, well be saying it only takes 800 sats to buy a dollar now. Get ready to price your Uber ride in millisats and your morning coffee in sats-per-milliliter. Sarcasm aside, the writing is on the wall: Bitcoin is becoming the unit of account for a new financial era and its happening faster than most expect.
